\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 INTERESTS:\b0 \i0 \ul0  The Minority Business Enterprise Legal Defense and Education Fund, Inc. ("MBELDEF") is a nonprofit corporation founded in 1980 by former Maryland Congressman Parren J. Mitchell.  The primary purpose of MBELDEF is to promote legally defensible minority business opportunity programs.  MBELDEF is comprised of over 2,000 minority businesses nationwide, many of which, in their efforts to become successful commercial enterprises, have benefited from federal, state, and local minority business opportunity programs.  Additionally, MBELDEF has provided numerous state and local governments with legal guidance in the adoption of such programs and has participated in significant litigation concerning these programs.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 INTEREST OF THE AMICUS CURIAE
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The National Minority Supplier Development Council, Inc. ("NMSDC") is a nonprofit corporation founded in 1969 that seeks to provide minority business with access to purchasing opportunities in the public and private sectors.  Currently, NMSDC has 46 regional offices and a national office that coordinates these efforts on a local and national level.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The National Black Chamber of Commerce, Inc. ("NBCC") is a nonprofit corporation, dedicated to the economic empowerment of African American communities through development of African American businesses, particularly manufacturing and construction.  NBCC has 80 affiliated chapters throughout the nation.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The National Association of Minority Contractors ("NAMC") is a nonprofit corporation founded in 1969.  During its 25 years of service, NAMC's goals have been to provide education and training to minority contractors, to promote the economic and legal interest of minority construction firms, and to bring equitable procurement and business opportunities to its membership.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 These Amici Curiae have a significant interest in this Court's review of the substantial constitutional issues presented by this challenge to programs that benefit minority business enterprises. n1 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n1 The parties have consented to the filing of this brief.  Their letters of consent are on file with the Clerk of the Court.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 INTRODUCTION AND SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This case raises issues of great social and jurisprudential importance.  Petitioner challenges the federal government's power to encourage the awarding of federal contracts to businesses owned by socially and economically disadvantaged persons.  Specifically, petitioner argues that the equal protection component of the Fifth Amendment invalidates longstanding federal efforts to assist disadvantaged persons because these programs incorporate rebuttable evidentiary presumptions that members of particular racial and ethnic groups suffer such disadvantage.  Even such limited, remedial consideration of race, petitioner urges, is generally forbidden to the federal government.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 These important issues should not be addressed in this case.  First, and quite remarkably, petitioner has never identified which set \b \i0 \ul0 [*4]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of federal statutes and regulations it is attacking.  At least three different sets of federal laws grant contracting preferences to businesses owned by socially and economically disadvantaged persons and are incorporated into the contract clause at issue here.  The record does not reveal which program is at issue, and any one of the three might have led to the challenged preference.  These programs differ in important respects, and those differences may make a critical difference in the constitutional analysis.  Furthermore, because of this confusion, the Court would either have to affirm or invalidate all the programs, whether or not they are placed at issue by the facts, thus rendering what may well be an advisory opinion.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Second, the record does not indicate whether a presumption based on race is even at issue.  Businesses can qualify as disadvantaged without any reliance on a racial presumption.  The record does not establish whether the subcontractor at issue qualified by virtue of a racial presumption or by direct proof of disadvantage.  Resolution of the question presented might well result in an advisory opinion for this reason as well.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 If this Court reaches the merits,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*5]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the decision below should be affirmed.  Strict equal protection scrutiny should not apply here.  Congress has substantial leeway -- more leeway than is afforded the States -- to make limited use of racial considerations to remedy disadvantages resulting from race discrimination.  The federal programs at issue do not grant preferences on the basis of race.  They grant unobjectionable preferences on the basis of social and economic disadvantage: both minority and non-minority individuals may qualify for statutory preferences.  Each program uses race as a basis for a rebuttable presumption of disadvantage, but where that presumption is questioned, each program also places minority applicants for disadvantaged status on equal footing with non-minority applicants by requiring the same proof of economic disadvantage from each.  Moreover, the contract clause at issue does not obligate private contractors to employ socially and economically disadvantaged subcontractors.  It merely provides compensation to those who choose to do so.  Thus, racial considerations play a carefully confined role in the overall scheme, and pose none of the risks that have required the application of strict scrutiny \b \i0 \ul0 [*6]\b0 \i0 \ul0   in other contexts.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 There is ample support for Congress' judgment that such programs remain necessary to combat social and economic disadvantage.  These federal laws, like all others, come to the Court with a presumption of constitutionality, and the record before Congress provides substantial evidence from which Congress could reasonably conclude that the challenged preferences remain necessary.  See Fullilove v. Klutznick, 448 U.S. 448 (1980). Cf.  Turner Broadcasting Systems, Inc. v. FCC, 114 S. Ct. 2445 (1994). Furthermore, a plethora of studies conducted in the wake of City of Richmond v. J. A. Croson Co., 488 U.S. 469 (1989), confirm the continuing pattern of discrimination at the state and local levels in all regions of the country -- and thus reinforce the continuing need for contracting preferences for the socially and economically disadvantaged.
\par \pard 
